      description: "Orly Airport is 25 min from Marnes-la-Coquette via the N118 and A6, a quick and scenic connection.",
      routeDescription: "Via the N118 from Vaucresson then the A6 to Orly.",
      introduction: "Marnes-la-Coquette is an exceptional residential enclave of barely 1,700 inhabitants, tucked into the wooded hillsides of the Hauts-de-Seine department and widely regarded as one of the most exclusive addresses in the entire Paris region. The commune covers just 215 hectares, making it the smallest municipality in the department, yet its landscape is remarkably varied: to the north, the 600-hectare Fausses-Reposes national forest — a protected expanse of ancient oaks and chestnuts — rolls all the way to the outskirts of Versailles, while to the south the tranquil ponds of Ville-d'Avray reflect the same willow-fringed scenery that Camille Corot captured on canvas in the nineteenth century. Within the village itself, narrow lanes wind between high meuliere stone walls concealing sprawling estates with manicured gardens, and multi-storey buildings are essentially absent from the skyline. The Institut Pasteur operates a research facility on the commune's territory, continuing a scientific presence that dates back to Louis Pasteur's own visits to the area. Marnes-la-Coquette also gained widespread recognition as the home of French rock icon Johnny Hallyday, whose imposing property on the hillside became a place of pilgrimage for fans. Positioned eight kilometres from the Palace of Versailles and five kilometres from the Chateau de Malmaison, the commune sits within a corridor of outstanding French heritage. However, Marnes-la-Coquette has no railway station, no metro link and no tram service — a defining feature that makes private transport essential for any meaningful journey. The route to Orly Airport via the N118 and A6 is one of the shortest and most scenic airport connections in western Paris, descending through forests and leafy hillsides before joining the motorway south.",
      itineraire: "From Marnes-la-Coquette, your driver descends via the D907 towards Vaucresson, reaching the N118 dual carriageway within just a few minutes of leaving your door. The N118 is a purpose-built expressway that runs southward along the heavily wooded hillsides of Chaville and Meudon, offering a surprisingly green and pleasant drive given its proximity to central Paris. The road passes above the Sevres bridge area and continues through a forested corridor, skirting the edge of Clamart before arriving at the Velizy-Villacoublay interchange. Here the driver merges onto the A6 motorway — the autoroute du Soleil — and follows the clearly signposted exit for Orly Airport. Toll charges on this route amount to roughly three euros, already included in the fixed fare. Under normal traffic conditions the entire journey takes approximately twenty-five minutes, making it one of the quickest airport transfers available from any commune in the Hauts-de-Seine. During the morning rush from 7:30 to 9:30 am or the evening peak from 5:00 to 7:30 pm, the N118 can experience slowdowns near the Sevres bridge and the Velizy interchange, extending the trip to between thirty and forty minutes. Your driver monitors real-time traffic conditions throughout and can divert through Chaville and Clamart on local roads if the N118 becomes saturated.",
      conseils: "For morning flights from Orly, plan to leave Marnes-la-Coquette at least one hour and fifteen minutes before your scheduled departure time. The N118 is typically free-flowing before seven in the morning, and traffic settles again between ten and four in the afternoon — these are the windows that yield the smoothest journeys. When booking, specify your Orly terminal number (1, 2, 3 or 4) so that your driver can drop you at the entrance closest to your airline's check-in desks, avoiding unnecessary walks through the terminal buildings. For return journeys, your driver will be waiting in the arrivals zone holding a sign with your name; real-time flight monitoring means they track any delays automatically, and a complimentary thirty-minute waiting period after actual landing is included in the fare. The seven-seat van option at seventy euros is ideal for families travelling with young children, car seats and bulky luggage that would be impractical to haul through public transport stations. Orly long-stay parking costs between twenty and twenty-eight euros per day, so a round-trip taxi booking at seventy to one hundred euros total becomes more economical for any absence of three days or longer. Because Marnes-la-Coquette has no rail or metro connections, we strongly recommend booking your return taxi at the same time as your outbound ride to guarantee a stress-free collection when you land back in Paris.",
      comparaisonTransport: "From Marnes-la-Coquette, reaching Orly by public transport is a genuinely arduous undertaking. The journey starts with a local bus — line 171 or 426 — to either Chaville or Garches station, a wait that can be unpredictable outside peak service hours. From there, a Transilien L or U train takes you towards central Paris, where you must transfer to the metro and then pick up either the OrlyBus coach or the T7 tramway for the final leg to the airport. The total travel time ranges from one hour thirty to a full two hours, involves three to four separate changes and requires navigating stairs, escalators and long connecting corridors — a punishing itinerary when you are carrying suitcases or travelling with small children. A taxi at thirty-five to fifty euros eliminates every one of those complications: a direct, comfortable twenty-five-minute drive from your front gate to the terminal entrance, with your driver handling the luggage. For two passengers the per-person cost is just eighteen to twenty-five euros, which is both faster and cheaper than ride-hailing apps during surge-pricing periods. For residents of Marnes-la-Coquette, where there is no direct transit link of any kind, the fixed-fare taxi is the only genuinely practical way to reach Orly Airport.",
